Kind of like how it happened with Ryan Gosling's Lost River. Like, I'm afraid that the movie will be purely "visual" with random stuff happening around without having a strong narrative development.  I will be seeing this one for sure, and I will be more than happy to be proven wrong, but at this point I'm really skeptical. I miss the early Refn where his movies literally kicked you in the gut (Pusher trilogy).  I'm still looking forward to it, and I'm crossing my fingers for a good reception at Cannes, but anyone else feel the same way?

text: Anyone going on about how this looks like Black Swan, that the only thing interesting are the visuals, and this is not a horror movie at all etc. Unfortunately none of these are the aims of Refn, if you have watched some of his earlier works ( and i'm not talking about Drive ) like the Pusher trilogy or Valhalla rising you'd see that his movies is what you make it to be, there is no clear message, he doesn't hand over plots Hollywood style like that, so it's not for everyone.   He tries to go down to those unexplicable uncharted bizarre and grotesque corners of human mind. There is no one character in this movie whom you can relate to, it's a showdown of the weird. And if you don't like how sexual theme's are portrayed you can always go and watch Big Mike XXL and 50 Shades of Grey.

text: I love how the trailer didn't really reveal anything significant like most trailers where they basically show the entire movie. The film itself was a beautiful piece of cinematography and behind it had such a deep meaning. At first I didn't quite understand it, but I did some digging around for an explanation and my God was this a masterpiece in showing the meaning. The way it was illustrated was truly magnificent and how every colour, being, mirror, etc was significant as well as linked to each other and the meanings. I love how it all progressively linked so subtly and how the graphic and shocking scenes did indeed get that "reaction" the director really wanted. It was a little slow and was really hard for me to decipher as I watched it, but once I researched behind it - it was a brilliant story, although perhaps a little slow or even tedious in places. I don't think I could watch it again for that. I prefer the Black Swan as a movie. Elle, I love her, was amazing, as with Jenna.

text: I saw it just yesterday. It's not only visually stunning. It's truly an experience.   Finally, Refn managed to merge his crafty direction with a layered and worthy story, he now has something to tell. A deep look at the dark core of what makes us human and to our beauty obsessed society.   People complain about the lack of character development, but the movie instead of forcing the characters to deliver, it's just faithful to them. People in the fashion business are portrayed just the way they are, empty. Souless. Merciless. Savages.   And the richest story is not in the words, because just like in a world where everything that matters it's is looks, the movie tells a story that way, with images and visuals.   It's perfect. I can't wait for NWR next project.   Ps. On a side note, Elle it's incredible. So I enjoyed to see Keanu on that kind of role, hope to see more of him experimenting.

text: Once again director Winding Refn shows that he appreciates film as an art form and gives us yet another unnusual, unconventional, grotesquely wonderful piece of art.  This film is probably the most shockingly and even more hedonistically movie he ever made, but that doesn't mean that there is something wrong in that approach. His vision of modelling world really worked here as he shows us literally how fucked up and damaged its participants are. Numerous times he speaks the truth in his unique way of expression and some times it may seem self indulging and narcissistic, but i found it beautiful and richening. Actors did a great job here, dialogue is smart and insightful, cinematography is gorgeous, and while the film is slow paced and clearly not fleshed out well, still it sends a subtle message for the target audience if you can read between the lines.

text: I don't understand the comparison to 'Black Swan'. Is it the visual similarity to another female driven "indie-looking" film featuring the thematic importance of beauty and a good amount of body horror? I can see that, but the movies are really different beyond that. Neon Demon is surrealist satire mixed with horror elements. There's really nothing psychological about it. The main character proceeds through the film with the bravado of strong myth then arrives at a point where the entire through line of the film flips on its head, signaling a metatextual balancing of forces, suggesting something insightful and truly terrifying about our society.  Many people will highlight the issues on the surface, but I recommend looking closer and instead of writing it off, let the film challenge you. Along with films like "The Lobster" and "The Handmaiden", 2016 has proven to have delivered some boldly realised and layered cinema.

Her dad just told her to "stay sweet", and they both abandon her.  -She dreams of a life of stardom, and is desperate to act grown up, and get all the attention. So she leaves home, and hitchhikes. Gets picked up by a cowboy, who charms her, but whom she also has lover's spats with. He soon thinks that they could be destined to be together. So he kidnaps, and rapes her. I think that the rape in particular, is relevant to Neon Demon, because Jesse wants to stay pure, at all costs. And doesn't even kiss a guy she actually likes. Not really indicative of having been assaulted, but Refn said that the scene in which Keanu's character sticks a knife in Jesse's mouth, was representative of how she imagines penetration to be. And of course, that's extreme, for someone who's only had normal, if any, sexual experience.   -There's also the end of Hick, where Alec Baldwin's character sends her to LA, to live with his sister, and go to a fancy school. I could imagine that during that time, she didn't really connect with his sister, or do well in school (probably because of bullying rooted in jealousy) dropped out, and ran away again, to pursue stardom. But with more maturity, this time.

text: I just saw this movie yesterday on a whim and was blown away. It's crazy how many negative reviews this got. I started it with no expectations and finished it realizing I had just watched a MASTERPIECE. Jaw-dropping visuals and soundtrack that makes every other movie look dull in comparison, the lack of dialogue is done purposefully as the visuals and the actor's expressions and body language do most of the talking. Multiple layers of meaning and symbolism throughout. This movie is a work of art, and anyone who thinks it's bad simply doesn't understand what they are watching.
author: Gunnar S

text: I feel like there's an important point people miss about this movie. While it seems like Jesse (Elle Fanning)¬†is the star of the movie and everything revolves around her, at the end we see this movie is actually about Sarah. Jesse is just the competition in her way that she needs to get rid of, and in the end she emerges victorious. The ruthless villain¬†willing to do anything ends up winning, as often is the case in real life. Another thing is, people say this movie is simply about the modeling industry and "instagram culture" when I see it more as applying to any cut-throat world such as the business or corporate world where others are seen as competitors and obstacles in the way to success. The cannibalism is just an allegory of this IMO, as she literally "ate" her competition. Brilliant movie.
author: Gunnar S
